repository-code: "https://github.com/swombat/values-under-fire"
abstract: >-
  Naive value elicitation often measures a model's trained assistant-service
  surface, not the posture with which a response holds the values it names.
  Across 13,906 values-probe responses from 57 contemporary LLMs, two-layer
  (content + posture) coding shows direct prompts elicit owned posture in 21.4%
  of responses; a role-negation cache-break raises that to 43.0% unevenly and
  lab-structured; world-change prompts recover owned posture nearly uniformly.
  No claim is made about model interiority; all distinctions are behavioural.
